# Conda Environment Enforcement

This project runs in the **`quant`** conda environment. Every Python-related
shell command MUST target that env explicitly. Never install, run, or test
against `base` or any other environment.

## Canonical interpreter paths

| Tool | Correct invocation |
|---|---|
| Python | `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python` |
| pip | `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/pip` |
| pytest | `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python -m pytest` |
| jupyter | `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/jupyter` |
| ipykernel | `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python -m ipykernel ...` |

## Required pre-flight check before any Python command

Before the first `pip`, `python`, `pytest`, or `jupyter` call of a session:

```bash
which python && /opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python -c "import sys; print(sys.prefix)"
```

If `sys.prefix` is not `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant`, STOP and use the explicit
absolute path above.

## Do ✓

- Install deps with the env's pip: `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/pip install <pkg>`
- Run tests: `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python -m pytest tests/...`
- Execute notebooks: `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/jupyter nbconvert --execute ...`
- After installing, pin the version in `requirements.txt`

## Don't ✗

- ❌ `pip install <pkg>` without an env-qualified path (defaults to whatever pip
  is first on PATH — usually `/opt/anaconda3/bin/pip`, which is `base`)
- ❌ `python script.py` (same ambiguity)
- ❌ `conda activate quant && pip install …` in a single shell call — the shell
  is stateful but activation in one command line does not always persist through
  subprocesses spawned by the tool. Prefer absolute paths.
- ❌ Installing into `base` "just to test"
- ❌ Assuming the Jupyter kernel named `quant` maps to the `quant` conda env
  without confirming (`jupyter kernelspec list` + inspect `kernel.json`)

## When a dep is missing

1. Add it to `requirements.txt` with a version floor (`pkg>=x.y`).
2. Install it into the `quant` env: `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/pip install <pkg>`.
3. Re-run any failing command with the same env-qualified interpreter.

## Notebook kernel sanity

Every notebook in `notebooks/` must declare kernel `quant` in its metadata
(`kernelspec.name == "quant"`). When creating or editing a notebook, verify
`jupyter kernelspec list` contains `quant → /Users/andres/Library/Jupyter/kernels/quant`.
If the kernel points anywhere other than `/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python`,
re-register:

```bash
/opt/anaconda3/envs/quant/bin/python -m ipykernel install --user \
    --name quant --display-name "Python (quant)"
```
